@MikeKalinowski Completely agree!

Those last two episode of "Loki" Season 1 were pretty good (all things considered).

I like that the final episode had the guts to do something the MCU never does (not the Feige branch anyway): it slowed down and allowed important moments to just... happen. Even through talking.

It's especially hard to square here because the show TRIES to reconcile the character's past by showing some "Avengers" footage & commenting on it - but this only highlights how incompatible that movie was with Loki's personality elsewhere.

@Mark_of_Bagwell @trigger_mister exactly, im saying what if spiderman had an arc where his cum was addictive and Mary Jane couldnt leave him because she had to drink his cum? Thats essentially SD now.

True, the director was fighting against that all the way with constant camera moving - dollying in & out, dutching, etc - but in the end, the episode was allowed to just take its time without driving forward with the usual relentless energy.

Good to see!

Now, I do feel like the show continued the MCU's trouble with handling Loki as a character outside of "Thor" movies.

Here, they just tried to pretend that he was a good (or, "misunderstood", "lonely") guy at heart. The opposite of Loki in "The Avengers" who was pure evil.
Is this year's #Eurovision being organised by Mysterio from Spider-Man?

Here, though, they go too far the other way. They try to just excuse his dark past as being about silly pranks to overcome his desire for companionship, his fear of being alone.

All so that he can work as a lead character. But this is a disservice to Loki.

If you have to swing hard one way, better the way "Loki" handles it than "The Avengers". But it doesn't have to be this binary. Good drama explores the ground in between.

THAT is where the inherent entertainment of the character is found. The show is OK but misses its potential.
